# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chase-gun
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:chase-gun/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] Apilan is a native Malay word, not descended from any foreign word.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] It is also a standalone word, because the syllable is api-lan instead of apil-an.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] The term comes from Malay word *kota* which in turn comes from the Sanskrit word कोट्ट (kota) which means fort, fortress, castle, fortified house, fortification, works, city, town, or place encircled by walls.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] The word *mara* may come from Malay word meaning "appear before", "forward", "come", "moved to the front", "forward", and "advanced".
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] Thus it can be interpreted as "breastwork before a cannon" or "breastwork at the front".
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] According to the Great Indonesian Dictionary (KBBI), kota mara means (1) Wall on a ship to protect men mounting the cannon (2) Terrace or wall over a castle which a cannon is mounted.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] Warington Smyth, kota mara means transverse deck bulkhead at stem and stern (of a ship).
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] *Benteng* itself means fort, battery, or redoubt.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] Singapore resident John Crawfurd recorded Malay piracy near Singapore waters.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] The Malay pirate ships of the time were 40–50 feet (12–15 m) long with 15-foot (4.6 m) beam.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] The decks were made of split *nibong* wood.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] Smaller pirate craft put up thick plank bulwarks [apilan] when fighting, while larger ones like those of the Lanun people had bamboo ledges hanging over their gunwales, with a protecting breastwork [kota mara] of plaited rattan about 3 feet (0.91 meters) high.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] A crew might consist of 20–30 men, augmented with oarsmen of captured slaves.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] Small craft would have nine oars per side; larger ones would be double-banked, with an upper tier of oarsmen seated on the bulwark projection hidden behind rattan breastwork.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] Pirate armament included a stockade near the bow, with iron or brass 4-pounders, and another stockade aft, generally with two swivel guns.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] They also might have four or five brass swivels, or rantaka, on each side.
[src:chase-gun/apilan-and-kota-mara] They have bamboo shields, and were armed with spears, keris, muskets and other firearms they could get.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] When used on its own, the word "autocannon" typically indicates a non-rotary weapon with a single barrel.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] When multiple rotating barrels are involved, such a weapon is referred to as a "rotary autocannon" or "rotary cannon".
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] If it uses a single barrel with a rotating cylinder with multiple chambers, it is known as a "revolver autocannon" or "revolver cannon"; both of these systems are commonly used as aircraft guns and anti-aircraft guns.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Autocannons are heavy weapons that are unsuitable for use by infantry.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Due to the heavy weight and recoil, they are typically installed on fixed mounts, wheeled carriages, ground combat vehicles, aircraft, or watercraft, and are almost always crew-served, or even remote-operated with automatic target recognition/acquisition (e.g. sentry guns and naval CIWS).
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] As such, ammunition is typically fed from a belt system to reduce reloading pauses or for a faster rate of fire, but magazines remain an option.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Common types of ammunition, among a wide variety, include HEIAP, HEDP and more specialised armour-piercing (AP) munitions, mainly composite rigid (APCR) and discarding sabot (APDS) rounds.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Capable of generating extremely rapid firepower, autocannons overheat quickly if used for sustained fire, and are limited by the amount of ammunition that can be carried by the weapons systems mounting them.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Both the US 25 mm M242 Bushmaster and the British 30 mm RARDEN have relatively slow rates of fire so as not to deplete ammunition too quickly.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The Oerlikon KBA 25 mm has a relatively mid-high rate of fire 650 rounds per minute but can be electronically programmed to 175–200 rounds per minute.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The rate of fire of a modern autocannon ranges from 90 rounds per minute, in the case of the British RARDEN, to 2,500 rounds per minute with the GIAT 30.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Rotary systems with multiple barrels can achieve over 10,000 rounds per minute (the Russian GSh-6-23, for example).
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Such extremely high rates of fire are effectively employed by aircraft in aerial dogfights and close air support on ground targets via strafing attacks, where the target dwell time is short and weapons are typically operated in brief bursts.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The first modern autocannon was the British QF 1-pounder, also known as the "pom-pom".
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] This was essentially an enlarged version of the Maxim gun, which was the first successful fully automatic machine gun, requiring no outside stimulus in its firing cycle other than holding the trigger.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The pom-pom fired 1 pound (0.45 kg) gunpowder-filled explosive shells at a rate of over 200 rounds a minute: much faster than conventional artillery while possessing a much longer range and more firepower than the infantry rifle.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] In 1913, Reinhold Becker and his *Stahlwerke Becker* firm designed the 20mm Becker cannon, addressing the German Empire's perceived need for heavy-calibre aircraft armament.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The Imperial Government's Spandau Arsenal assisted them in perfecting the ordnance.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The Imperial Japanese Navy's Type 99 cannon, adopted and produced in 1939, was also based on the Becker/Oerlikon design's principles.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] During the First World War, autocannons were mostly used in the trenches as anti-aircraft guns.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The British used pom-pom guns as part of their air defences to counter the German Zeppelin airships that made regular bombing raids on London.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] However, they were of little value, as their shells neither ignited the hydrogen of the Zeppelins nor caused sufficient loss of gas (and hence lift) to bring them down.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Attempts to use the guns in aircraft failed, as the weight severely limited both speed and altitude, thus making successful interception impossible.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The more effective QF 2 pounder naval gun would be developed during the war to serve as an anti-aircraft and close range defensive weapon for naval vessels.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Autocannons would serve to a much greater extent and effect during the Second World War.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The German Panzer II light tank, which was one of the most numerous in German service during the invasion of Poland and the campaign in France, used a 20 mm autocannon as its main armament.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Although ineffective against tank armour even during the early years of the war, the cannon was effective against light-skinned vehicles as well as infantry and was also used by armoured cars.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Larger examples, such as the 40 mm Vickers S, were mounted in ground attack aircraft to serve as an anti-tank weapon, a role to which they were suited as tank armour is often lightest on top.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The Polish 20 mm 38 Fk auto cannon was expensive to produce, but an exception.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Unlike the Oerlikon, it was effective against all the tanks fielded in 1939, largely because it was built as an upgrade to the Oerlikon, Hispano-Suiza, and Madsen.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] It even proved capable of knocking out early Panzer IIIs and IVs, albeit with great difficulty.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Only 55 were produced by the time of the Polish Defensive War.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] However it was in the air war that these weapons played their most important part in the conflict.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] During the First World War, rifle-calibre machine guns became the standard weapons of military aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] In the Second, several factors brought about their replacement by autocannon.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] During the inter-war years, aircraft underwent extensive evolution and the all-metal monoplane, pioneered as far back as the end of 1915, almost entirely replaced wood and fabric biplanes.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] At the same time as they began to be made from stronger materials, the machines also increased in speed, streamlining, power and size, and it began to be apparent that correspondingly more powerful weapons would be needed to counter them.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Conversely, they were becoming much better able to carry exactly such larger and more powerful guns; the technology of which was in the meantime also developing, providing significantly improved rates of fire and reliability.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] When the Second World War did break out, it was swiftly realised that the power of contemporary aircraft allowed armour plate to be fitted to protect the pilot and other vulnerable areas.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] This innovation proved highly effective against rifle-calibre machine gun rounds, which tended to ricochet off harmlessly.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Similarly the introduction of self sealing fuel tanks provided reliable protection against these small projectiles.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Nevertheless, the U.S. also adopted planes fitted with autocannon, such as the Lockheed P-38 Lightning, despite experiencing technical difficulties with developing and manufacturing these large-calibre automatic guns.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Weapons such as the Oerlikon 20 mm, the Bofors 40 mm and various German Rheinmetall autocannons would see widespread use by both sides during the Second World War; not only in an anti-aircraft role, but as a weapon for use against ground targets as well.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Heavier anti-aircraft cannon had difficulty tracking fast-moving aircraft and were unable to accurately judge altitude or distance, while machine guns possessed insufficient range and firepower to bring down aircraft consistently.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Continued ineffectiveness against aircraft despite the large numbers installed during the second World War led, in the West, to the removal of almost all shipboard anti-aircraft weapons in the early post-war period.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] This was only reversed with the introduction of computer-controlled systems.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The German *Luftwaffe* deployed small numbers of the experimental *Bordkanone* series of heavy aircraft cannon in 37, 50 and 75 mm calibres, mounted in gun pods under the fuselage or wings.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The 37 mm BK 3,7 cannon, based on the German Army's 3.7 cm FlaK 43 anti-aircraft autocannon was mounted in pairs in underwing gun pods on a small number of specialized Stuka *Panzerknacker* (tank buster) aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The BK 5 cm cannon, based on the 5 cm KwK 39 cannon of the Panzer III, was installed in Ju 88P bomber destroyers, which also used other *Bordkanone* models, and in the Messerschmitt 410 *Hornisse* (Hornet) bomber destroyer.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] 300 examples of the BK 5 cannon were built, more than all other versions.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The PaK 40 semi-automatic 7.5 cm calibre anti-tank gun was the basis for the BK 7,5 in the Junkers Ju 88 P-1 heavy fighter and Henschel Hs 129 B-3 twin engined ground attack aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The German Mauser MK 213 was developed at the end of the Second World War and is regarded as the archetypal modern revolver cannon.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] With multiple chambers and a single barrel, autocannons using the revolver principle can combine a very high rate of fire and high acceleration to its maximum firing rate with low weight, at cost of a reduced sustained rate of fire compared to rotary cannon.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] They are, therefore, used mainly in aircraft for AA purposes, in which a target is visible for a short period of time.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The development of guided missiles was thought to render cannons unnecessary, and a full generation of western fighter aircraft was built without them.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] In contrast, all Eastern Bloc aircraft kept their guns.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] This was particularly important during the Vietnam War where the rules of engagement constrained pilots from engaging targets beyond visual range.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] As a consequence, fighters at the time had cannons added back in external "gun pods", and virtually all fighter aircraft retain autocannons in integral internal mounts to this day.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] After the Second World War, autocannons continued to serve as a versatile weapon in land, sea, and air applications.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Examples of modern autocannons include the 25 mm Oerlikon KBA mounted on the IFV Freccia, the M242 Bushmaster mounted on the M2/M3 Bradley, updated versions of the Bofors 40 mm gun, and the Mauser BK-27.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] The 20 mm M61A1 is an example of an electrically powered rotary autocannon.
[src:chase-gun/autocannon] Another role that has come into association with autocannons are that of close-in weapon systems on naval vessels, which are used to destroy anti-ship missiles and low flying aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] The **bow** (/baʊ/) is the forward part of the hull of a ship or boat, the point that is farthest forward when the vessel is underway in the usual direction.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] A ship's bow should be designed to enable the hull to pass efficiently through the water.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] Bow shapes vary according to the speed of the boat, the seas or waterways being navigated, and the vessel's function.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] Where sea conditions are likely to promote pitching, it is useful if the bow provides reserve buoyancy; a flared bow (a raked stem with flared topsides) is ideal to reduce the amount of water shipped over the bow.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] Ideally, the bow's shape should both reduce water resistance and block water from regularly washing over the top of it.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] Large commercial barges on inland waterways rarely meet big waves and may have remarkably little freeboard at the bow, whereas fast military vessels operating offshore must be able to cope with heavy seas.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] On slower ships like tankers and barges, a fuller bow shape is used to maximise the volume of the ship for a given length.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] The bow may be reinforced to serve as an ice-breaker.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] The forward part of the bow is called the "stem" or "forestem".
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] Traditionally, the stem was a timber (or metal) post into which side planks (or plates) were joined.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] Some boats such as the Dutch barge "aak" or the clinker-built Viking longships have no straight stem, having instead a curved prow.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] From Middle Dutch *boech* (modern spelling *boeg*).
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] Although "bow" has the same ultimate origin as "bough" (from the Old English *bóg*, or *bóh* (shoulder, the bough of a tree), the nautical term is unrelated, being unknown in this use in English before 1600.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] The "prow" (French: *proue*, Latin: *prora*) is the foremost part of a ship's bow above the waterline.
[src:chase-gun/bow-watercraft] The terms *prow* and "bow" are often used interchangeably to describe the foremost part of a ship and its surrounding parts.
[src:chase-gun/bowsprit] The **bowsprit** of a sailing vessel is a spar extending forward from the vessel's prow.
[src:chase-gun/bowsprit] The bowsprit is typically held down by a bobstay that counteracts the forces from the forestays.
[src:chase-gun/bowsprit] The bowsprit’s purpose is to create anchor points for the sails that extend beyond the vessel’s bow, increasing the size of sail that may be held taut.
[src:chase-gun/bowsprit] The word *bowsprit* is thought to originate from the Middle Low German word *bōchsprēt* – *bōch* meaning "bow" and *sprēt* meaning "pole".
[src:chase-gun/bowsprit] On some square-rigged ships a spritsail is flown below the bowsprit; these are sometimes accompanied by a sprit topmast, which serves to assist the spritsail while tacking.
[src:chase-gun/bowsprit] The bowsprit may also be used to hold up the figurehead.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] From the 16th century until the early decades of the steamship, vessels had rows of guns set in each side of the hull.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Firing all guns on one side of the ship became known as a "broadside".
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] The cannons of 18th-century men of war were accurate only at short range, and their penetrating power mediocre, which meant that the thick hulls of wooden ships could only be pierced at short ranges.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] These wooden ships sailed closer and closer towards each other until cannon fire would be effective.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Each tried to be the first to fire a broadside, often giving one party a decisive headstart in the battle when it crippled the other ship.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Since ancient times, war at sea had been fought much like on land: with melee weapons and bows and arrows, but on floating wooden platforms rather than battlefields.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Though the introduction of firearms was a significant change, it only slowly changed the dynamics of ship-to-ship combat.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] The first guns on ships were small wrought-iron pieces mounted on the open decks and in the fighting tops, often requiring only one or two men to handle them.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] They were designed to injure, kill or simply stun, shock and frighten the enemy prior to boarding.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] As guns were made more durable to withstand stronger gunpowder charges, they increased their potential to inflict critical damage to the vessel rather than just its crew.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Since these guns were much heavier than the earlier anti-personnel weapons, they had to be placed lower in the ships, and fire from gunports, to avoid ships becoming unstable.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] In Northern Europe the technique of building ships with clinker planking made it difficult to cut ports in the hull; clinker-built (or clench-built) ships had much of their structural strength in the outer hull.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] The solution was the gradual adoption of carvel-built ships that relied on an internal skeleton structure to bear the weight of the ship.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] The development of propulsion during the 15th century from single-masted, square-rigged cogs to three-masted carracks with a mix of square and lateen sails made ships nimbler and easier to maneuver.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Gunports cut in the hull of ships were introduced, according to tradition, in 1501 by Breton shipwright called Descharges, but it is just as likely to have been a gradual adaptation of loading ports in the stern of merchant vessels that had already been in use for centuries.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Initially, the gunports were used to mount heavy stern chasers pointing aft, but soon gun ports migrated to the sides of ships.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] This made possible coordinated volleys from all the guns on one side of a ship for the first time in history, at least in theory.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Guns in the 16th century were considered to be in fixed positions and were intended to be fired independently rather than in concerted volleys.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] It was not until the 1590s that the word "broadside" in English was commonly used to refer to gunfire from the side of a ship rather than the ship's side itself.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] The main batteries in 20th century battleships tended to be powered gun turrets which could swivel 180 degrees or more to establish wider firing arcs around the entire vessel.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Additionally, directing the guns to the port or starboard side projected the massive muzzle blast out over the ocean, while firing the guns too close to the deck could cause damage to the ship.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] When the term is used in this way, it can be calculated by multiplying the shell weight of the ship's main armament shells times the number of barrels that can be brought to bear.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] If some turrets are incapable of firing to either side of the vessel, only the maximum number of barrels which can fire to one side or the other are counted.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] For example, the American *Iowa*-class battleships carried a main armament of nine 16-inch (406 mm) main guns in turrets which could all be trained to a single broadside.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Each 16-inch shell weighed 2,700 pounds (1,200 kg), which when multiplied by nine (the total number of barrels in all three turrets) equals a total of 24,300 pounds (11,022 kg).
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] Thus, an *Iowa*-class battleship had a broadside of 12 short tons (11.0 tonnes), the weight of shells that she could theoretically land on a target in a single firing.
[src:chase-gun/broadside-naval] See list of broadsides of major World War II ships for a comparison.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] A **cannon** (plural either *cannons* or *cannon*) is a large-caliber gun classified as a type of artillery, which usually launches a projectile using explosive chemical propellant.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Gunpowder ("black powder") was the primary propellant before the invention of smokeless powder during the late 19th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons vary in gauge, effective range, mobility, rate of fire, angle of fire and firepower; different forms of cannon combine and balance these attributes in varying degrees, depending on their intended use on the battlefield.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] A cannon is a type of heavy artillery weapon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from several languages, in which the original definition can usually be translated as *tube*, *cane*, or *reed*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of cannons may have appeared in Song dynasty China as early as the 12th century; however, solid archaeological and documentary evidence of cannons do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In 1288, Yuan dynasty troops are recorded to have used hand cannons in combat, and the earliest extant cannon bearing a date of production comes from the same period.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century, cannons were widespread throughout Eurasia.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons were used primarily as anti-infantry weapons until around 1374, when large cannons were recorded to have breached walls for the first time in Europe.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons featured prominently as siege weapons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In 1464 a 16,000 kg (35,000 lb) cannon known as the Great Turkish Bombard was created in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons as field artillery became more important after 1453 when cannons broke down the walls of the Roman Empire's capital, with the introduction of limber, which greatly improved cannon maneuverability and mobility.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] European cannons reached their longer, lighter, more accurate, and more efficient "classic form" around 1480.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] This classic European cannon design stayed relatively consistent in form with minor changes until the 1750s.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In the modern era, the term *cannon* has fallen into disuse, replaced by *guns* or *artillery*, if not a more specific term such as howitzer or mortar, except for automatic weapons called autocannons, usually firing explosive shells of larger caliber than machine-gun bullets.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The word *cannon* is derived from the Old Italian word *cannone*, meaning "large tube", which came from the Latin *canna*, in turn originating from the Greek κάννα (*kanna*), "reed", and then generalised to mean any hollow tube-like object.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The word has been used to refer to a gun since 1326 in Italy and 1418 in England.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The plural forms *cannons* and *cannon* are both correct.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The cannon may have appeared as early as the 12th century in China, and was probably a parallel development or evolution of the fire-lance, a short ranged anti-personnel weapon combining a gunpowder-filled tube and a polearm.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Projectiles such as iron scraps or porcelain shards, mixed together with the gunpowder ("co-viative"), were placed in fire lance barrels at some point, and eventually, the paper and bamboo materials of fire lance barrels were replaced by metal.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The earliest known depiction of a cannon is a sculpture from the Dazu Rock Carvings in Sichuan dated to 1128, however, the earliest archaeological samples and textual accounts do not appear until the 13th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The primary extant specimens of cannon from the 13th century are the Wuwei Bronze Cannon dated to 1227, the Heilongjiang hand cannon dated to 1288, and the Xanadu Gun dated to 1298.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] However, only the Xanadu gun contains an inscription bearing a date of production, so it is considered the earliest confirmed extant cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Xanadu Gun is 34.7 cm (13.7 in) in length and weighs 6.2 kg (14 lb).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The other cannons are dated using contextual evidence.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Heilongjiang hand cannon is also often considered by some to be the oldest firearm since it was unearthed near the area where the *History of Yuan* reports a battle took place involving hand cannons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] According to the *History of Yuan*, in 1288, a Jurchen commander by the name of Li Ting led troops armed with hand cannons into battle against the rebel prince Nayan.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Chen Bingying argues there were no guns before 1259, while Dang Shoushan believes the Wuwei gun and other Western Xia era samples point to the appearance of guns by 1220, and Stephen Haw goes even further by stating that guns were developed as early as 1200.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Sinologist Joseph Needham and renaissance siege expert Thomas Arnold provide a more conservative estimate of around 1280 for the appearance of the "true" cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Whether or not any of these are correct, it seems likely that the gun was born sometime during the 13th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] References to cannons proliferated throughout China in the following centuries.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In 1341 Xian Zhang wrote a poem called *The Iron Cannon Affair* describing a cannonball fired from an eruptor which could "pierce the heart or belly when striking a man or horse, and even transfix several persons at once." By the 1350s the cannon was used extensively in Chinese warfare.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In 1358 the Ming army failed to take a city due to its garrisons' usage of cannon, however, they themselves would use cannon, in the thousands, later on during the siege of Suzhou in 1366.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Mongol invasion of Java in 1293 brought gunpowder technology to the Nusantara archipelago in the form of cannon (Chinese: *Pao*).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] During the Ming dynasty cannons were used in riverine warfare at the Battle of Lake Poyang.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] One shipwreck in Shandong had a cannon dated to 1377 and an anchor dated to 1372.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] From the 13th to 15th centuries cannon-armed Chinese ships also travelled throughout Southeast Asia.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannon appeared in Đại Việt by 1390 at the latest.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The first of the western cannon to be introduced were breech-loaders in the early 16th century, which the Chinese began producing themselves by 1523 and improved on by including composite metal construction in their making.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Japan did not acquire cannon until 1510 when a monk brought one back from China, and did not produce any in appreciable numbers.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] During the 1593 siege of Pyongyang, 40,000 Ming troops deployed a variety of cannons against Japanese troops.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Despite their defensive advantage and the use of arquebus by Japanese soldiers, the Japanese were at a severe disadvantage due to their lack of cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Throughout the Japanese invasions of Korea (1592–1598), the Ming–Joseon coalition used artillery widely in land and naval battles, including on the turtle ships of Yi Sun-sin.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] According to Ivan Petlin, the first Russian envoy to Beijing, in September 1619, the city was armed with large cannon with cannonballs weighing more than 30 kg (66 lb).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Outside of China, the earliest texts to mention gunpowder are Roger Bacon's *Opus Majus* (1267) and *Opus Tertium* in what has been interpreted as references to firecrackers.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In the early 20th century, a British artillery officer proposed that another work tentatively attributed to Bacon, *Epistola de Secretis Operibus Artis et Naturae, et de Nullitate Magiae*, dated to 1247, contained an encrypted formula for gunpowder hidden in the text.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] These claims have been disputed by science historians.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In any case, the formula itself is not useful for firearms or even firecrackers, burning slowly and producing mostly smoke.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] There is a record of a gun in Europe dating to 1322 that was discovered in the nineteenth century, but the artifact has since been lost.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In the same year, another similar illustration showed a darker gun being set off by a group of knights, in another work of de Milemete's, *De secretis secretorum Aristotelis*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] On 11 February of that same year, the Signoria of Florence appointed two officers to obtain *canones de mettallo* and ammunition for the town's defence.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In the following year a document from the Turin area recorded a certain amount was paid "for the making of a certain instrument or device made by Friar Marcello for the projection of pellets of lead".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] A reference from 1331 describes an attack mounted by two Germanic knights on Cividale del Friuli, using man-portable gunpowder weapons of some sort.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The 1320s seem to have been the takeoff point for guns in Europe according to most modern military historians.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Scholars suggest that the lack of gunpowder weapons in a well-travelled Venetian's catalogue for a new crusade in 1321 implies that guns were unknown in Europe up until this point, further solidifying the 1320 mark, however more evidence in this area may be forthcoming in the future.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The oldest extant cannon in Europe is a small bronze example unearthed in Loshult, Scania in southern Sweden.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] It dates from the early-mid 14th century, and is currently in the Swedish History Museum in Stockholm.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Early cannons in Europe often shot arrows and were known by an assortment of names such as *pot-de-fer*, *tonnoire*, *ribaldis*, and *büszenpyle*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The *ribaldis*, which shot large arrows and simplistic grapeshot, were first mentioned in the English Privy Wardrobe accounts during preparations for the Battle of Crécy, between 1345 and 1346.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Florentine Giovanni Villani recounts their destructiveness, indicating that by the end of the battle, "the whole plain was covered by men struck down by arrows and cannon balls".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Similar cannon were also used at the siege of Calais (1346–47), although it was not until the 1380s that the *ribaudekin* clearly became mounted on wheels.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Battle of Crécy which pitted the English against the French in 1346 featured the early use of cannon which helped the longbowmen repulse a large force of Genoese crossbowmen deployed by the French.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The English originally intended to use the cannon against cavalry sent to attack their archers, thinking that the loud noises produced by their cannon would panic the advancing horses along with killing the knights atop them.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Early cannons could also be used for more than simply killing men and scaring horses.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] English cannon were used defensively in 1346 during the siege of Breteuil to launch fire onto an advancing siege tower.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In this way, cannons could be used to burn down siege equipment before it reached the fortifications.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The use of cannons to shoot fire could also be used offensively as another battle involved the setting of a castle ablaze with similar methods.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The particular incendiary used in these projectiles was most likely a gunpowder mixture.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] This is one area where early Chinese and European cannons share a similarity as both were possibly used to shoot fire.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Early European cannons were rather small, dwarfed by the bombards, which would come later.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In fact, it is possible that the cannons used at Crécy were capable of being moved rather quickly as there is an anonymous chronicle that notes the guns being used to attack the French camp, indicating that they would have been mobile enough to press the attack.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] These smaller cannons would eventually give way to larger, wall-breaching guns by the end of the 1300s.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] There is no clear consensus on when the cannon first appeared in the Islamic world, with dates ranging from 1260 to the mid-14th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] However, some scholars do not accept these early dates.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] While the date of its first appearance is not entirely clear, the general consensus among most historians is that there is no doubt the Mamluk forces were using cannon by 1342.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Other accounts may have also mentioned the use of cannon in the early 14th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] An Arabic text dating to 1320–1350 describes a type of gunpowder weapon called a *midfa* which uses gunpowder to shoot projectiles out of a tube at the end of a stock.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Some scholars consider this a hand cannon while others dispute this claim.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Nasrid army besieging Elche in 1331 made use of "iron pellets shot with fire".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] According to historian Ahmad Y. al-Hassan, during the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, the Mamluks used cannon against the Mongols.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] He claims that this was "the first cannon in history" and used a gunpowder formula almost identical to the ideal composition for explosive gunpowder.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] He also argues that this was not known in China or Europe until much later.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Al-Hassan further claims that the earliest textual evidence of cannon is from the Middle East, based on earlier originals which report hand-held cannons being used by the Mamluks at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Such an early date is not accepted by some historians, including David Ayalon, Iqtidar Alam Khan, Joseph Needham and Tonio Andrade.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Khan argues that it was the Mongols who introduced gunpowder to the Islamic world, and believes cannon only reached Mamluk Egypt in the 1370s.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Needham argued that the term *midfa*, dated to textual sources from 1342 to 1352, did not refer to true hand-guns or bombards, and that contemporary accounts of a metal-barrel cannon in the Islamic world did not occur until 1365.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Similarly, Andrade dates the textual appearance of cannons in middle eastern sources to the 1360s.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Gabor Ágoston and David Ayalon note that the Mamluks had certainly used siege cannons by 1342 or the 1360s, respectively, but earlier uses of cannons in the Islamic World are vague with a possible appearance in the Emirate of Granada by the 1320s and 1330s, though evidence is inconclusive.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Ibn Khaldun reported the use of cannon as siege machines by the Marinid sultan Abu Yaqub Yusuf at the siege of Sijilmasa in 1274.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The passage by Ibn Khaldun on the Marinid siege of Sijilmassa in 1274 occurs as follows: "[The Sultan] installed siege engines ... and gunpowder engines ..., which project small balls of iron.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] These balls are ejected from a chamber ... placed in front of a kindling fire of gunpowder; this happens by a strange property which attributes all actions to the power of the Creator." The source is not contemporary and was written a century later, around 1382.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Needham believes Ibn Khaldun was speaking of fire lances rather than hand cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Ottoman Empire made good use of cannon as siege artillery.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Sixty-eight super-sized bombards were used by Mehmed the Conqueror to capture Constantinople in 1453.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Jim Bradbury argues that Urban, a Hungarian cannon engineer, introduced this cannon from Central Europe to the Ottoman realm; according to Paul Hammer, however, it could have been introduced from other Islamic countries which had earlier used cannons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] These cannons could fire heavy stone balls a mile, and the sound of their blast could reportedly be heard from a distance of 10 miles (16 km).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Shkodëran historian Marin Barleti discusses Turkish bombards at length in his book *De obsidione Scodrensi* (1504), describing the 1478–79 siege of Shkodra in which eleven bombards and two mortars were employed.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Ottomans also used cannon to control passage of ships through the Bosphorus strait.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Ottoman cannons also proved effective at stopping crusaders at Varna in 1444 and Kosovo in 1448 despite the presence of European cannon in the former case.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The similar Dardanelles Guns (for the location) were created by Munir Ali in 1464 and were still in use during the Anglo-Turkish War (1807–1809).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] These were cast in bronze into two parts: the chase (the barrel) and the breech, which combined weighed 18.4 tonnes.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The two parts were screwed together using levers to facilitate moving it.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Fathullah Shirazi, a Persian inhabitant of India who worked for Akbar in the Mughal Empire, developed a volley gun in the 16th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] While there is evidence of cannons in Iran as early as 1405 they were not widespread.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] This changed following the increased use of firearms by Shah Ismail I, and the Iranian army used 500 cannons by the 1620s, probably captured from the Ottomans or acquired by allies in Europe.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] By 1443, Iranians were also making some of their own cannon, as Mir Khawand wrote of a 1200 kg metal piece being made by an Iranian *rikhtegar* which was most likely a cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Due to the difficulties of transporting cannon in mountainous terrain, their use was less common compared to their use in Europe.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Documentary evidence of cannons in Russia does not appear until 1382 and they were used only in sieges, often by the defenders.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] It was not until 1475 when Ivan III established the first Russian cannon foundry in Moscow that they began to produce cannons natively.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The earliest surviving cannon from Russia dates to 1485.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Later on, large cannons were known as bombards, ranging from three to five feet in length and were used by Dubrovnik and Kotor in defence during the later 14th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The first bombards were made of iron, but bronze became more prevalent as it was recognized as more stable and capable of propelling stones weighing as much as 45 kilograms (99 lb).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Around the same period, the Byzantine Empire began to accumulate its own cannon to face the Ottoman Empire, starting with medium-sized cannon 3 feet (0.91 m) long and of 10 in calibre.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The earliest reliable recorded use of artillery in the region was against the Ottoman siege of Constantinople in 1396, forcing the Ottomans to withdraw.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Ottomans acquired their own cannon and laid siege to the Byzantine capital again in 1422.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] By 1453, the Ottomans used 68 Hungarian-made cannon for the 55-day bombardment of the walls of Constantinople, "hurling the pieces everywhere and killing those who happened to be nearby".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The largest of their cannons was the Great Turkish Bombard, which required an operating crew of 200 men and 70 oxen, and 10,000 men to transport it.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Gunpowder made the formerly devastating Greek fire obsolete, and with the final fall of Constantinople—which was protected by what were once the strongest walls in Europe—on 29 May 1453, "it was the end of an era in more ways than one".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons were introduced to the Javanese Majapahit Empire when Kublai Khan's Mongol-Chinese army under the leadership of Ike Mese sought to invade Java in 1293.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] *History of Yuan* mentioned that the Mongol used a weapon called *p'ao* against Daha forces.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] This weapon is interpreted differently by researchers, it may be a trebuchet that throws thunderclap bombs, firearms, cannons, or rockets.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] It is possible that the gunpowder weapons carried by the Mongol–Chinese troops amounted to more than one type.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Thomas Stamford Raffles wrote in *The History of Java* that in 1247 saka (1325 AD), cannons were widely used in Java especially by the Majapahit.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] It is recorded that the small kingdoms in Java that sought the protection of Majapahit had to hand over their cannons to the Majapahit.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Majapahit under *Mahapatih* (prime minister) Gajah Mada (in office 1331–1364) utilized gunpowder technology obtained from Yuan dynasty for use in naval fleet.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Mongol-Chinese gunpowder technology of Yuan dynasty resulted in eastern-style cetbang which is similar to Chinese cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Swivel guns however, only developed in the archipelago because of the close maritime relations of the Nusantara archipelago with the territory of West India after 1460 AD, which brought new types of gunpowder weapons to the archipelago, likely through Arab intermediaries.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] This weapon seems to be cannon and gun of Ottoman tradition, for example the prangi, which is a breech-loading swivel gun.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] A new type of cetbang, called the western-style cetbang, was derived from the Turkish prangi.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Just like prangi, this cetbang is a breech-loading swivel gun made of bronze or iron, firing single rounds or scattershots (a large number of small bullets).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons derived from western-style cetbang can be found in Nusantara, among others were lantaka and lela.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Most lantakas were made of bronze and the earliest ones were breech-loaded.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] There is a trend toward muzzle-loading weapons during colonial times.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] When the Portuguese came to the archipelago, they referred to the breech-loading swivel gun as *berço*, while the Spaniards call it *verso*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] A pole gun (*bedil tombak*) was recorded as being used by Java in 1413.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] 1514 said that the inhabitants of Java were great masters in casting artillery and very good artillerymen.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] They made many one-pounder cannon (*cetbang* or *rentaka*), long muskets, *spingarde* (arquebus), *schioppi* (hand cannon), Greek fire, guns (cannon), and other fireworks.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Every place was considered excellent in casting artillery, and in the knowledge of using it.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In 1513, the Javanese fleet led by Pati Unus sailed to attack Portuguese Malacca "with much artillery made in Java, for the Javanese are skilled in founding and casting, and in all works in iron, over and above what they have in India".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] By early 16th century, the Javanese already locally-producing large guns, some of them still survived until the present day and dubbed as "sacred cannon" or "holy cannon".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] These cannons varied between 180- and 260-pounders, weighing anywhere between 3 and 8 tons, length of them between 3 and 6 m (9.8 and 19.7 ft).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons were used by the Ayutthaya Kingdom in 1352 during its invasion of the Khmer Empire.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Within a decade large quantities of gunpowder could be found in the Khmer Empire.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] By the end of the 14th century firearms were also used by the Trần dynasty.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Saltpeter harvesting was recorded by Dutch and German travellers as being common in even the smallest villages and was collected from the decomposition process of large dung hills specifically piled for the purpose.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The Dutch punishment for possession of non-permitted gunpowder appears to have been amputation.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Ownership and manufacture of gunpowder was later prohibited by the colonial Dutch occupiers.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] According to colonel McKenzie quoted in Sir Thomas Stamford Raffles' *The History of Java* (1817), the purest sulfur was supplied from a crater from a mountain near the straits of Bali.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In Africa, the Adal Sultanate and the Abyssinian Empire both deployed cannons during the Adal-Abyssinian War.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Imported from Arabia, and the wider Islamic world, the Adalites led by Ahmed ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi were the first African power to introduce cannon warfare to the African continent.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Later on as the Portuguese Empire entered the war it would supply and train the Abyssinians with cannons, while the Ottoman Empire sent soldiers and cannon to back Adal.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] The conflict proved, through their use on both sides, the value of firearms such as the matchlock musket, cannon, and the arquebus over traditional weapons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] While previous smaller guns could burn down structures with fire, larger and more powerful cannons forced engineers to develop stronger castle walls from enemy attacks.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons were used for other purposes, as fortifications began using cannons as defensive instruments.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In India, the fort of Raicher had gun ports built into its walls to accommodate the use of defensive cannons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In *The Art of War*, Niccolò Machiavelli opined that field artillery forced an army to take up a defensive posture and opposed a more ideal offensive stance.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Machiavelli's concerns can be seen in the criticisms of Portuguese mortars being used in India during the sixteenth century as lack of mobility was one of the key problems with the design.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] In Russia the early cannons were again placed in forts as a defensive tool.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p01] Cannons were also difficult to move around in mountainous regions; offensives conducted with such weapons would often be unsuccessful in areas such as Iran.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] By the 16th century, cannons were made in a great variety of lengths and bore diameters, but the general rule was that the longer the barrel, the longer the range.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Some cannons made during this time had barrels exceeding 10 ft (3.0 m) in length, and could weigh up to 20,000 pounds (9,100 kg).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Consequently, large amounts of gunpowder were needed to allow them to fire stone balls several hundred yards.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] By mid-century, European monarchs began to classify cannons to reduce the confusion.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Henry II of France opted for six sizes of cannon, but others settled for more; the Spanish used twelve sizes, and the English sixteen.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] They are, from largest to smallest: the cannon royal, cannon, cannon serpentine, bastard cannon, demicannon, pedrero, culverin, basilisk, demiculverin, bastard culverin, saker, minion, falcon, falconet, serpentine, and rabinet.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Better powder had been developed by this time as well.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Instead of the finely ground powder used by the first bombards, powder was replaced by a "corned" variety of coarse grains.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] This coarse powder had pockets of air between grains, allowing fire to travel through and ignite the entire charge quickly and uniformly.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The end of the Middle Ages saw the construction of larger, more powerful cannon, as well as their spread throughout the world.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] As they were not effective at breaching the newer fortifications resulting from the development of cannon, siege engines—such as siege towers and trebuchets—became less widely used.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] However, wooden "battery-towers" took on a similar role as siege towers in the gunpowder age—such as that used at Siege of Kazan in 1552, which could hold ten large-calibre cannon, in addition to 50 lighter pieces.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Another notable effect of cannon on warfare during this period was the change in conventional fortifications.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Niccolò Machiavelli wrote, "There is no wall, whatever its thickness that artillery will not destroy in only a few days." Although castles were not immediately made obsolete by cannon, their use and importance on the battlefield rapidly declined.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Instead of majestic towers and merlons, the walls of new fortresses were thick, angled, and sloped, while towers became low and stout; increasing use was also made of earth and brick in breastworks and redoubts.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] These new defences became known as bastion forts, after their characteristic shape which attempted to force any advance towards it directly into the firing line of the guns.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] A few of these featured cannon batteries, such as the House of Tudor's Device Forts in England.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Bastion forts soon replaced castles in Europe and, eventually, those in the Americas as well.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] By the end of the 15th century, several technological advancements made cannons more mobile.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Wheeled gun carriages and trunnions became common, and the invention of the limber further facilitated transportation.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] As a result, field artillery became more viable and began to see more widespread use, often alongside the larger cannons intended for sieges.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Better gunpowder, cast-iron projectiles (replacing stone), and the standardisation of calibres meant that even relatively light cannons could be deadly.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Despite the increased maneuverability, however, cannon were still the slowest component of the army: a heavy English cannon required 23 horses to transport, while a culverin needed nine.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Even with this many animals pulling, they still moved at a walking pace.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Due to their relatively slow speed, lack of organisation, and undeveloped tactics, the combination of pike and shot still dominated the battlefields of Europe.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Innovations continued, notably the German invention of the mortar, a thick-walled, short-barrelled gun that blasted shot upward at a steep angle.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Mortars were useful for sieges, as they could hit targets behind walls or other defences.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] This cannon found more use with the Dutch, who learnt to shoot bombs filled with powder from them.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] "Single firing" was first used to ignite the fuse, where the bomb was placed with the fuse down against the cannon's propellant.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] This often resulted in the fuse being blown into the bomb, causing it to blow up as it left the mortar.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Because of this, "double firing" was tried where the gunner lit the fuse and then the touch hole.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] This required considerable skill and timing, and was especially dangerous if the gun misfired, leaving a lighted bomb in the barrel.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Not until 1650 was it accidentally discovered that double-lighting was superfluous as the heat of firing would light the fuse.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden emphasised the use of light cannon and mobility in his army, and created new formations and tactics that revolutionised artillery.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] He discontinued using all 12 pounder—or heavier—cannon as field artillery, preferring, instead, to use cannons that could be handled by only a few men.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] One obsolete type of gun, the "leatheren", was replaced by 4 pounder and 9 pounder demi-culverins.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] These could be operated by three men, and pulled by only two horses.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Gustavus Adolphus's army was also the first to use a cartridge that contained both powder and shot which sped up reloading, increasing the rate of fire.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Finally, against infantry he pioneered the use of canister shot—essentially a tin can filled with musket balls.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Until then there was no more than one cannon for every thousand infantrymen on the battlefield but Gustavus Adolphus increased the number of cannons sixfold.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Each regiment was assigned two pieces, though he often arranged them into batteries instead of distributing them piecemeal.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] He used these batteries to break his opponent's infantry line, while his cavalry would outflank their heavy guns.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Breitenfeld, in 1631, Adolphus proved the effectiveness of the changes made to his army, by defeating Johann Tserclaes, Count of Tilly.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Although severely outnumbered, the Swedes were able to fire between three and five times as many volleys of artillery, and their infantry's linear formations helped ensure they did not lose any ground.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Battered by cannon fire, and low on morale, Tilly's men broke ranks and fled.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] In England, cannons were being used to besiege various fortified buildings during the English Civil War.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Nathaniel Nye is recorded as testing a Birmingham cannon in 1643 and experimenting with a saker in 1645.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] From 1645 he was the master gunner to the Parliamentarian garrison at Evesham and in 1646 he successfully directed the artillery at the Siege of Worcester, detailing his experiences and in his 1647 book *The Art of Gunnery*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Believing that war was as much a science as an art, his explanations focused on triangulation, arithmetic, theoretical mathematics, and cartography as well as practical considerations such as the ideal specification for gunpowder or slow matches.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] His book acknowledged mathematicians such as Robert Recorde and Marcus Jordanus as well as earlier military writers on artillery such as Niccolò Fontana Tartaglia and Thomas (or Francis) Malthus (author of *A Treatise on Artificial Fire-Works*).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Around this time also came the idea of aiming the cannon to hit a target.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Gunners controlled the range of their cannons by measuring the angle of elevation, using a "gunner's quadrant".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannons did not have sights; therefore, even with measuring tools, aiming was still largely guesswork.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] In the latter half of the 17th century, the French engineer Sébastien Le Prestre de Vauban introduced a more systematic and scientific approach to attacking gunpowder fortresses, in a time when many field commanders "were notorious dunces in siegecraft".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Careful sapping forward, supported by enfilading ricochets, was a key feature of this system, and it even allowed Vauban to calculate the length of time a siege would take.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] He was also a prolific builder of bastion forts, and did much to popularize the idea of "depth in defence" in the face of cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] These principles were followed into the mid-19th century, when changes in armaments necessitated greater depth defence than Vauban had provided for.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] It was only in the years prior to World War I that new works began to break radically away from his designs.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The lower tier of 17th-century English ships of the line were usually equipped with demi-cannons, guns that fired a 32-pound (15 kg) solid shot, and could weigh up to 3,400 pounds (1,500 kg).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Demi-cannons were capable of firing these heavy metal balls with such force that they could penetrate more than a metre of solid oak, from a distance of 90 m (300 ft), and could dismast even the largest ships at close range.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Full cannon fired a 42-pound (19 kg) shot, but were discontinued by the 18th century, as they were too unwieldy.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] By the end of the 18th century, principles long adopted in Europe specified the characteristics of the Royal Navy's cannon, as well as the acceptable defects, and their severity.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The United States Navy tested guns by measuring them, firing them two or three times—termed "proof by powder"—and using pressurized water to detect leaks.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The carronade was adopted by the Royal Navy in 1779; the lower muzzle velocity of the round shot when fired from this cannon was intended to create more wooden splinters when hitting the structure of an enemy vessel, as they were believed to be more deadly than the ball by itself.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The carronade was much shorter, and weighed between a third to a quarter of the equivalent long gun; for example, a 32-pounder carronade weighed less than a ton, compared with a 32-pounder long gun, which weighed over 3 t (3.0 long tons; 3.3 short tons).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The guns were, therefore, easier to handle, and also required less than half as much gunpowder, allowing fewer men to crew them.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Carronades were manufactured in the usual naval gun calibres, but were not counted in a ship of the line's rated number of guns.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] As a result, the classification of Royal Navy vessels in this period can be misleading, as they often carried more cannons than were listed.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannons were crucial in Napoleon's rise to power, and continued to play an important role in his army in later years.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] During the French Revolution, the unpopularity of the Directory led to riots and rebellions.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] When over 25,000 royalists led by General Danican assaulted Paris, Paul Barras was appointed to defend the capital; outnumbered five to one and disorganised, the Republicans were desperate.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] When Napoleon arrived, he reorganised the defences but realised that without cannons the city could not be held.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] He ordered Joachim Murat to bring the guns from the Sablons artillery park; the Major and his cavalry fought their way to the recently captured cannons, and brought them back to Napoleon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] When Danican's poorly trained men attacked, on 13 Vendémiaire 1795 (5 October in the calendar used in France at the time), Napoleon ordered his cannon to fire grapeshot into the mob, an act that became known as the "whiff of grapeshot".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The slaughter effectively ended the threat to the new government, while, at the same time, making Bonaparte a famous—and popular—public figure.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Among the first generals to recognise that artillery was not being used to its full potential, Napoleon often massed his cannon into batteries and introduced several changes into the French artillery, improving it significantly and making it among the finest in Europe.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Such tactics were successfully used by the French, for example, at the Battle of Friedland, when 66 guns fired a total of 3,000 roundshot and 500 rounds of grapeshot, inflicting severe casualties to the Russian forces, whose losses numbered over 20,000 killed and wounded, in total.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] At the Battle of Waterloo—Napoleon's final battle—the French army had many more artillery pieces than either the British or Prussians.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] As the battlefield was muddy, recoil caused cannons to bury themselves into the ground after firing, resulting in slow rates of fire, as more effort was required to move them back into an adequate firing position; also, roundshot did not ricochet with as much force from the wet earth.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Despite the drawbacks, sustained artillery fire proved deadly during the engagement, especially during the French cavalry attack.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The British infantry, having formed infantry squares, took heavy losses from the French guns, while their own cannons fired at the cuirassiers and lancers, when they fell back to regroup.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Eventually, the French ceased their assault, after taking heavy losses from the British cannon and musket fire.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] In the 1810s and 1820s, greater emphasis was placed on the accuracy of long-range gunfire, and less on the weight of a broadside.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Around 1822, George Marshall wrote *Marshall's Practical Marine Gunnery*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The book was used by cannon operators in the United States Navy throughout the 19th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] It listed all the types of cannons and instructions.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The carronade, although initially very successful and widely adopted, disappeared from the Royal Navy in the 1850s after the development of wrought-iron-jacketed steel cannon by William Armstrong and Joseph Whitworth.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Nevertheless, carronades were used in the American Civil War.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Western cannons during the 19th century became larger, more destructive, more accurate, and could fire at longer range.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] One example is the American 3-inch (76 mm) wrought-iron, muzzle-loading rifle, or Griffen gun (usually called the 3-inch Ordnance Rifle), used during the American Civil War, which had an effective range of over 1.1 mi (1.8 km).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Another is the smoothbore 12-pounder Napoleon, which originated in France in 1853 and was widely used by both sides in the American Civil War.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] This cannon was renowned for its sturdiness, reliability, firepower, flexibility, relatively lightweight, and range of 1,700 m (5,600 ft).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The practice of rifling—casting spiralling lines inside the cannon's barrel—was applied to artillery more frequently by 1855, as it gave cannon projectiles gyroscopic stability, which improved their accuracy.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] One of the earliest rifled cannons was the breech-loading Armstrong Gun—also invented by William Armstrong—which boasted significantly improved range, accuracy, and power than earlier weapons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The projectile fired from the Armstrong gun could reportedly pierce through a ship's side and explode inside the enemy vessel, causing increased damage and casualties.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The British military adopted the Armstrong gun, and was impressed; the Duke of Cambridge even declared that it "could do everything but speak".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Despite being significantly more advanced than its predecessors, the Armstrong gun was rejected soon after its integration, in favour of the muzzle-loading pieces that had been in use before.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] While both types of gun were effective against wooden ships, neither had the capability to pierce the armour of ironclads; due to reports of slight problems with the breeches of the Armstrong gun, and their higher cost, the older muzzle-loaders were selected to remain in service instead.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The superior cannon of the Western world brought them tremendous advantages in warfare.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] For example, in the First Opium War in China, during the 19th century, British battleships bombarded the coastal areas and fortifications from afar, safe from the reach of the Chinese cannons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Similarly, the shortest war in recorded history, the Anglo-Zanzibar War of 1896, was brought to a swift conclusion by shelling from British cruisers.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannons in the 20th and 21st centuries are usually divided into sub-categories and given separate names.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Some of the most widely used types of modern cannon are howitzers, mortars, guns, and autocannon, although a few very large-calibre cannon, custom-designed, have also been constructed.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Nuclear artillery was experimented with, but was abandoned as impractical.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Modern artillery is used in a variety of roles, depending on its type.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] According to NATO, the general role of artillery is to provide fire support, which is defined as "the application of fire, coordinated with the manoeuvre of forces to destroy, neutralize, or suppress the enemy".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] When referring to cannons, the term *gun* is often used incorrectly.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] By the early 20th century, infantry weapons had become more powerful, forcing most artillery away from the front lines.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Despite the change to indirect fire, cannons proved highly effective during World War I, directly or indirectly causing over 75% of casualties.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The onset of trench warfare after the first few months of World War I greatly increased the demand for howitzers, as they were more suited to hitting targets in trenches.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Furthermore, their shells carried more explosives than those of guns, and caused considerably less barrel wear.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The German army had the advantage here as they began the war with many more howitzers than the French.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] World War I also saw the use of the Paris Gun, the longest-ranged gun ever fired.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] This 200 mm (8 in) calibre gun was used by the Germans against Paris and could hit targets more than 122 km (76 mi) away.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The Second World War sparked new developments in cannon technology.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Among them were sabot rounds, hollow-charge projectiles, and proximity fuses, all of which increased the effectiveness of cannon against specific targets.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The proximity fuse emerged on the battlefields of Europe in late December 1944.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Used to great effect in anti-aircraft projectiles, proximity fuses were fielded in both the European and Pacific Theatres of Operations; they were particularly useful against V-1 flying bombs and kamikaze planes.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Although widely used in naval warfare, and in anti-air guns, both the British and Americans feared unexploded proximity fuses would be reverse engineered, leading to them limiting their use in continental battles.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] During the Battle of the Bulge, however, the fuses became known as the American artillery's "Christmas present" for the German army because of their effectiveness against German personnel in the open, when they frequently dispersed attacks.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Anti-tank guns were also tremendously improved during the war: in 1939, the British used primarily 2 pounder and 6 pounder guns.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] By the end of the war, 17 pounders had proven much more effective against German tanks, and 32 pounders had entered development.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Meanwhile, German tanks were continuously upgraded with better main guns, in addition to other improvements.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] For example, the Panzer III was originally designed with a 37 mm gun, but was mass-produced with a 50 mm cannon.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] To counter the threat of the Russian T-34s, another, more powerful 50 mm gun was introduced, only to give way to a larger 75 mm cannon, which was in a fixed mount as the StuG III, the most-produced German World War II armoured fighting vehicle of any type.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Despite the improved guns, production of the Panzer III was ended in 1943, as the tank still could not match the T-34, and was replaced by the Panzer IV and Panther tanks.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] In 1944, the 8.8 cm KwK 43 and many variations, entered service with the Wehrmacht, and was used as both a tank main gun, and as the PaK 43 anti-tank gun.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful guns to see service in World War II, it was capable of destroying any Allied tank at very long ranges.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Despite being designed to fire at trajectories with a steep angle of descent, howitzers can be fired directly, as was done by the 11th Marine Regiment at the Battle of Chosin Reservoir, during the Korean War.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Two field batteries fired directly upon a battalion of Chinese infantry; the Marines were forced to brace themselves against their howitzers, as they had no time to dig them in.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The Chinese infantry took heavy casualties, and were forced to retreat.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The tendency to create larger calibre cannons during the World Wars has reversed since.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The United States Army, for example, sought a lighter, more versatile howitzer, to replace their aging pieces.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] As it could be towed, the M198 was selected to be the successor to the World War II–era cannons used at the time, and entered service in 1979.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Still in use today, the M198 is, in turn, being slowly replaced by the M777 Ultralightweight howitzer, which weighs nearly half as much and can be more easily moved.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Although land-based artillery such as the M198 are powerful, long-ranged, and accurate, naval guns have not been neglected, despite being much smaller than in the past, and, in some cases, having been replaced by cruise missiles.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] However, the *Zumwalt*-class destroyer's planned armament included the Advanced Gun System (AGS), a pair of 155 mm guns, which fire the Long Range Land-Attack Projectile.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The warhead, which weighed 24 pounds (11 kg), had a circular error of probability of 50 m (160 ft), and was mounted on a rocket, to increase the effective range to 100 nmi (190 km), further than that of the Paris Gun.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The AGS's barrels would be water-cooled, and fire 10 rounds per minute, per gun.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The combined firepower from both turrets would give a *Zumwalt*-class destroyer the firepower equivalent to 12 conventional M198 howitzers.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The reason for the re-integration of cannons as a main armament in United States Navy ships was because satellite-guided munitions fired from a gun would be less expensive than a cruise missile but have a similar guidance capability.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Autocannons automatically fire a series of projectiles, similarly to a machine gun.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] They have mechanisms to automatically load their ammunition, and have a high rate of fire often approaching, or, in the case of rotary autocannons, even surpassing the firing rate of a machine gun.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Autocannons are usually of larger calibre than machine guns, typically 20 mm (0.8 in) or greater, and can usually fire explosive shells, unlike machine guns.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Explosive ammunition weighing less than 400 grams, as used by machine-gun calibres, is additionally banned in international conflict for parties to the Saint Petersburg Declaration of 1868.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Most nations use rapid-fire cannon on light vehicles, instead of a more powerful, but heavier, tank gun with a low rate of fire.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] A typical autocannon is the 25 mm US "Bushmaster" chain gun, mounted on the LAV-25 and M2 Bradley armoured vehicles.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The typical rate of fire for a modern autocannon ranges from 90 to 1,800 rounds per minute; systems with multiple barrels, such as rotary autocannon, can have rates of fire of several thousand rounds per minute.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The fastest of these is the GSh-6-23, which has a rate of fire of over 10,000 rounds per minute.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Autocannons are often fitted in aircraft and as shipboard anti-aircraft weapons, as they provide greater destructive power than previously-used machine guns.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The first documented installation of a cannon firing explosive shells on an aircraft was on the Voisin Canon in 1911, displayed at the Paris Exposition that year.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] By World War I, all of the major powers were experimenting with aircraft-mounted cannons; however, their low rate of fire and great size and weight precluded any of them from being anything other than experimental.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The most successful (or least unsuccessful) was the SPAD 12 Ca.1 single-seat fighter with a single 37 mm Puteaux mounted to fire between the cylinder banks and through the propeller boss of the aircraft's Hispano-Suiza 8C engine.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The pilot (by necessity an ace) had to manually load one round at a time.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The first autocannon were developed during World War I as anti-aircraft guns, and one of these, the Coventry Ordnance Works "COW 37 mm gun", was installed in an aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] However, the war ended before it could be given a field trial, and it never became standard equipment in a production aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Later trials had it fixed at a steep angle upwards in both the Vickers Type 161 and the Westland C.O.W.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Gun Fighter, an idea that returned later.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] During this period autocannons became available, and several fighters of the German *Luftwaffe* and the Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service were fitted with 20 mm cannons.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] They continued to be installed as an adjunct to machine guns rather than as a replacement, as the rate of fire was too low and each gun was too heavy.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] There was some debate in the RAF as to whether the greater number of possible rounds being fired from a machine gun, or a smaller number of explosive rounds from a cannon was preferable.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Improvements during the war in regards to rate of fire allowed the cannon to displace the machine gun almost entirely.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannons were more effective than machine-guns against armour, so they came increasingly into use in World War II; newer fighter aircraft such as the Hawker Tempest usually carried two or four instead of the six to twelve machine guns of earlier aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The Hispano-Suiza HS.404, Oerlikon 20 mm cannon, MG FF, and their numerous variants became among the most widely used autocannon in the war.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Aircraft cannons, as with machine guns, were either fixed to fire forwards (mounted in the wings, in the nose or fuselage, or in a pannier under either), typically on manoeuvrable fighters, or mounted movably in manned gun turrets on heavier less agile aircraft such as bombers.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Both the Germans and Japanese mounted cannons to fire upwards and forwards for use against heavy bombers, with the Germans calling guns so-installed *Schräge Musik*, derived from a German colloquialism for jazz music—*schräg* means "off-key".
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Nearly all modern fighter aircraft are armed with an autocannon, and they are also commonly fitted on ground-attack aircraft.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] One of the most powerful examples is the 30mm GAU-8/A Avenger Gatling-type rotary cannon mounted on the Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The Lockheed AC-130 gunship, based on a transport aircraft, can carry a 105 mm howitzer and a variety of autocannons ranging up to 40 mm.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Both are used in the close air support role.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannons in general have the form of a truncated cone with an internal cylindrical bore for holding an explosive charge and a projectile.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The thickest, strongest, and closed part of the cone is located near the explosive charge.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] As any explosive charge will dissipate in all directions equally, the thickest portion of the cannon is useful for containing and directing this force.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Field artillery cannon in Europe and the Americas were initially made most often of bronze, though later forms were constructed of cast iron and eventually steel.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] However, cast-iron cannon have a tendency to burst without having shown any previous weakness or wear, and this makes them more dangerous to operate.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The older and more-stable forms of cannon were muzzle-loading as opposed to breech-loading—to be used they had to have their ordnance packed down the bore through the muzzle rather than inserted through the breech.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The following terms refer to the components or aspects of a classical western cannon (c.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] In what follows, the words *near*, *close*, and *behind* will refer to those parts towards the thick, closed end of the piece, and *far*, *front*, *in front of*, and *before* to the thinner, open end.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] is determined by the diameter of its bore.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] made of copper screwed into the length of the vent.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The main body of a cannon consists of three basic extensions: the foremost and the longest is called the *chase*, the middle portion is the *reinforce*, and the closest and briefest portion is the *cascabel* or *cascable*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The chase is simply the entire conical part of the cannon in front of the *reinforce*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] the narrowest part of the chase, always located near the foremost end of the piece.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] these are a second series of such rings located at the near end of the chase.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] To pack a muzzle-loading cannon, first gunpowder is poured down the bore.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] This is followed by a layer of wadding (often nothing more than paper), and then the cannonball itself.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] A certain amount of windage (in this case meaning that the bore is designed slightly wider than the cannonball) allows the ball to fit down the bore, though the greater the windage the less efficient the propulsion of the ball when the gunpowder is ignited.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] To fire the cannon, the fuse located in the vent is lit, quickly burning down to the gunpowder, which then explodes violently, propelling wadding and ball down the bore and out of the muzzle.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] A small portion of exploding gas also escapes through the vent, but this does not dramatically affect the total force exerted on the ball.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] *Gun* in this context specifically refers to a type of cannon that fires projectiles at high speeds, and usually at relatively low angles; they have been used in warships, and as field artillery.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The term *cannon* is also used for autocannon, a modern repeating weapon firing explosive projectiles.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannon have been used extensively in fighter aircraft since World War II.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] In the 1770s, cannon operation worked as follows: each cannon would be manned by two gunners, six soldiers, and four officers of artillery.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The right gunner was to prime the piece and load it with powder, and the left gunner would fetch the powder from the magazine and be ready to fire the cannon at the officer's command.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] On each side of the cannon, three soldiers stood, to ram and sponge the cannon, and hold the ladle.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The second soldier on the left was tasked with providing 50 bullets.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Before loading, the cannon would be cleaned with a wet sponge to extinguish any smouldering material from the last shot.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Fresh powder could be set off prematurely by lingering ignition sources.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The powder was added, followed by wadding of paper or hay, and the ball was placed in and rammed down.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] After ramming, the cannon would be aimed with the elevation set using a quadrant and a plummet.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] At 45 degrees, the ball had the utmost range: about ten times the gun's level range.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Any angle above a horizontal line was called random-shot.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Wet sponges were used to cool the pieces every ten or twelve rounds.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] During the Napoleonic Wars, a British gun team consisted of five gunners to aim it, clean the bore with a damp sponge to quench any remaining embers before a fresh charge was introduced, and another to load the gun with a bag of powder and then the projectile.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The fourth gunner pressed his thumb on the vent hole, to prevent a draught that might fan a flame.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The charge loaded, the fourth would prick the bagged charge through the vent hole, and fill the vent with powder.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] On command, the fifth gunner would fire the piece with a slow match.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Friction primers replaced slow match ignition by the mid-19th century.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] When a cannon had to be abandoned such as in a retreat or surrender, the touch hole of the cannon would be plugged flush with an iron spike, disabling the cannon (at least until metal boring tools could be used to remove the plug).
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] A gun was said to be *honeycombed* when the surface of the bore had cavities, or holes in it, caused by corrosion or casting defects.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] In the United States, muzzleloading cannons made before 1899 (and replicas) that are unable to fire fixed ammunition are considered antiques.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] They are not subject to the Gun Control Act of 1968 or National Firearms Act of 1934.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] They may be subject to local rules in some jurisdictions, however.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Historically, logs or poles have been used as decoys to mislead the enemy as to the strength of an emplacement.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The "Quaker Gun trick" was used by Colonel William Washington's Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War; in 1780, approximately 100 Loyalists surrendered to them, rather than face bombardment.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] During the American Civil War, Quaker guns were also used by the Confederates, to compensate for their shortage of artillery.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The decoy cannon were painted black at the "muzzle", and positioned behind fortifications to delay Union attacks on those positions.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] On occasion, real gun carriages were used to complete the deception.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannon sounds have sometimes been used in classical pieces with a military theme.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] One of the best known examples is Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky's *1812 Overture*.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The overture is to be performed using an artillery section together with the orchestra, resulting in noise levels high enough that musicians are required to wear ear protection.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The cannon fire simulates Russian artillery bombardments of the Battle of Borodino, a critical battle in Napoleon's invasion of Russia, whose defeat the piece celebrates.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] When the overture was first performed, the cannon were fired by an electric current triggered by the conductor.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] However, the overture was not recorded with real cannon fire until Mercury Records and conductor Antal Doráti's 1958 recording of the Minnesota Orchestra.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannon fire is also frequently used in presentations of the *1812* on American Independence Day, a tradition started by Arthur Fiedler of the Boston Pops in 1974.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The hard rock band AC/DC used cannon fire in their song "For Those About to Rock (We Salute You)", and in live shows replica Napoleonic cannons and pyrotechnics were used to perform the piece.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] A recording of that song has accompanied the firing of an authentic reproduction of a M1857 12-pounder Napoleon during Columbus Blue Jackets goal celebrations at Nationwide Arena since opening night of the 2007–08 season.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The cannon is the focal point of the team's alternate logo on its third jerseys.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannons have been fired in touchdown celebrations by several American football teams including the San Diego Chargers.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The Pittsburgh Steelers used one only during the 1962 campaign but discontinued it after Buddy Dial was startled by inadvertently running face-first into the cannon's smoky discharge in a 42–27 loss to the Dallas Cowboys.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannon recovered from the sea are often extensively damaged from exposure to salt water; electrolytic reduction treatment is required to forestall corrosion.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] The cannon is then washed in deionized water to remove the electrolyte, and is treated in tannic acid, which prevents further rust and gives the metal a bluish-black colour.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] Cannon on display may be protected from oxygen and moisture by a wax sealant.
[src:chase-gun/cannon-p02] A coat of polyurethane may also be painted over the wax sealant, to prevent the cannon from attracting dust.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] A **chase gun** (or **chaser**), usually distinguished as **bow chaser** and **stern chaser**, was a cannon mounted in the bow (aiming forward) or stern (aiming backward) of a sailing ship.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] They were used to attempt to slow down an enemy ship either chasing (pursuing) or being chased, when the ship's broadside could not be brought to bear.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Typically, the chasers were used to attempt to damage the rigging and thereby cause the target to lose performance.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Bow chasers could be regular guns brought up from the gundeck and aimed through specially cut-out ports on either side of the bowsprit, or dedicated weapons made with an unusually long bore and a relatively light ball, and mounted in the bow.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Stern chasers could also be improvised, or left permanently in the cabins at the stern, covered up and used as part of the furniture.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] In the Age of Sail, shiphandling had been brought to a high art, and chases frequently lasted for hours or sometimes days, as each crew fine-tuned their sails to take advantage of small variations in the wind.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Chase guns of this era were commonly made of brass rather than iron, as this improved their accuracy.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] A single lucky shot could cut through a critical line, or cause a sail to split if the wind was strong, so if the ships were within range the best gunners on each would use their chasers to make carefully aimed and timed shots at the other.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Despite this, most chase guns were of limited accuracy even when aiming at the sizeable target of an enemy ship's rigging.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] In one eighteenth-century example, a British crew fired seventy-two shots from their vessels' bow chasers before hitting the sails of a fleeing enemy craft.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] By the late eighteenth century, Royal Navy crews were progressively being trained in the use of artillery in chases.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] The cannons themselves were also modified to maximise their effectiveness as chase guns, including reshaping of their gun carriages to allow for greater elevation and longer range.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] From 1799 Royal Navy frigates were universally supplied with two bow and two stern chasers, as these were the vessels most likely to be engaged in the pursuit of fleeing enemies.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Chase guns forward, or aft-facing naval guns were reintroduced during the Second World War in a modernised form aboard escort destroyers, corvettes, and motor gun boats.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Their role was to provide immediate offensive capability against surfaced U-boats and fast E-boats without needing to manoeuvre or rely on depth charges.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] In this regard, being used from a high and weatherly bow against small targets with a very low profile, their tactical employment was intended to remove a blind spot through a vertical arc (below the prow at short range) rather than through a narrow horizontal arc at longer ranges.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] On convoy escorts, particularly Hunt-class destroyers and Flower-class corvettes, bow-mounted chase guns were used to engage surfaced U-boats.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] Ships would illuminate the submarine with searchlights, then open fire with chase-mounted weapons aimed at the conning tower or pressure hull, forcing the U-boat to dive and abort its attack.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] This tactic was effective before the widespread deployment of forward throwing anti-submarine weapons like the Hedgehog or Squid.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] German E-boats (*Schnellboote*), fast torpedo craft used in the English Channel and North Sea, posed a major threat to coastal convoys.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] To counter these, many British escorts, especially Hunt-class destroyers, were fitted with a bow-mounted QF 2-pounder "pom-pom" autocannons as chase guns.
[src:chase-gun/chase-gun] One example occurred during a 1945 patrol by *HMS Cubitt*, when her forward-mounted pom-pom opened fire on an approaching group of E-boats.
